Explanation:

1. Initialize a 2D array dp to store the length of the longest substring formed by concatenating words from words array.
2. Iterate through the words array and update dp[i] to the length of the longest substring formed by concatenating words[i] and words[i+1] if the characters at positions i and i+1 match.
3. Iterate through the string s and for each index i, iterate through the remaining characters in s starting from index i+1. Check if the characters at positions i and i+1 match. If they do, update the result with i+j where dp[i] != -1 and dp[j] != -1.
4. Return the result.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n^2) because of the nested loops. The space complexity is O(n) due to the 2D array dp. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs a few comparisons and array accesses, which is efficient in terms of energy consumption.

